<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910719-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>910719-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- American Brands Inc.:   Increase in Earnings of 15%   Is Posted for Second Period</HL><DATE>07/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18</SO><CO>   AMB</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>BEVERAGES (BVG)DISTILLERS AND BREWERS, MAKERS OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES (DST)EARNINGS (ERN)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)EUROPE (EU)NORTH AMERICA (NME)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   American Brands Inc. said net income rose 15% in thesecond quarter on strong U.S. tobacco operations andfavorable foreign currency fluctuations.   The Old Greenwich, Conn., maker of tobacco, liquor andother consumer products said net for the quarter was $182million, or 88 cents a share, compared with $158 million, or81 cents a share. Revenue was essentially flat at $2.9billion.</LP><TEXT>   Chairman William J. Alley noted the results wereimpressive in light of the current recessions in the U.S. andBritain, and recent rises in the countries' excise taxes.Overall tobacco operations were down slightly, but U.S.tobacco, led by some new lower-priced cigarettes like BullDurham, had stronger operating profit.   Operating profit for distilled spirits was up 9%. Majorbrands include Jim Beam and Whyte andamp; Mackay whiskies. Itsother core businesses, life insurance, hardware and officeand specialty products, had mixed results.   In the first half, net increased 13% to $398 million, or$1.94 a share, from $354 million, or $1.81 a share. Revenuerose 10% to $6.8 billion. Fluctuations in foreign exchange,particularly for the British pound, increased revenue about$366 million.</TEXT></DOC>